<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/Sport/Article&sz=300x250&c=638894468&t=artid%3d5c14e6ea-0aac-4a90-ba88-cb5ca6bf5134%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/Sport/Article&sz=300x250&c=638894468&t=artid%3d5c14e6ea-0aac-4a90-ba88-cb5ca6bf5134%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>But today’s match will be a different ball game – and will matter even more because the winners will book their place in the final to be played at Levy Mwanawasa Stadium in Ndola on Saturday. Amajita reached the final of the competition last year, losing 2-1 to Zambia at Moruleng Stadium in Rustenburg. To overcome Egypt for a second time, Thabo Senong’s charges will need to avoid repeating the mistakes they made on Monday, where they found themselves trailing 1-0 in the first half despite creating several scoring opportunities. Amajita will be without two key players in defence, workaholic captain Thendo Mukumela and goalkeeper Khulekani Kubheka, who are both suspended.Senong said it did not worry them as it was a chance for other players to shine. Malebogo Modise is expected to lead the team in the absence of Mukumela.“Two players are suspended but for us we don’t see challenges – it’s another opportunity for two players to represent Amajita at international level. “We came here with 20 players, we will easily replace them,” said Senong.The coach admitted, however, that the Egyptians are not an easy nut to crack. “We are fully aware that knockout stages are a different ball game,” Senong said. “The mental demands will be different, but we are looking forward to the game. “We came here to develop our players and they understand how I want them to play. We are proud of what the boys have accomplished so far.”
